### Proof Sketch

First, we note that `rotproj_outer_unit` is defined as:
```
def rotproj_outer_unit (S : ℝ³) (w : ℝ²) (x : ℝ²) : ℝ :=
  ⟪rotM (x 0) (x 1) S, w⟫ / ‖S‖
```
In the statement `GlobalTheoremPrecondition.fu_outer`, `S` is replaced by `P`:
```
def GlobalTheoremPrecondition.fu_outer {pbar : Pose} {ε : ℝ} {poly : GoodPoly} (P : ℝ³)
    (pc : GlobalTheoremPrecondition poly pbar ε) : ℝ² → ℝ :=
  rotproj_outer_unit P pc.w
```

The theorem `GlobalTheoremPrecondition.fu_outer_pose_eq` involves `p.outerParams`, which is an element of `ℝ²`. Therefore, applying `GlobalTheoremPrecondition.fu_outer P pc` to `p.outerParams` gives:
```
rotproj_outer_unit P pc.w p.outerParams = ⟪rotM (p.outerParam 0) (p.outerParam 1) P, pc.w⟫ / ‖P‖
```

But `p.outerParams = (p.θ₂, p.φ₂)`, and `p.outer = rotM p.θ₂ p.φ₂`. So,
```
rotM (p.outerParam 0) (p.outerParam 1) P = rotM p.θ₂ p.φ₂ P = p.outer P
```
Thus:
```
rotproj_outer_unit P pc.w p.outerParams = ⟪p.outer P, pc.w⟫ / ‖P‖
```

Therefore:
```
GlobalTheoremPrecondition.fu_outer P pc p.outerParams * ‖P‖ = ⟪p.outer P, pc.w⟫
```

But since `inner ℝ a b = inner ℝ b a`, we have:
```
⟪p.outer P, pc.w⟫ = ⟪pc.w, p.outer P⟫
```

